


     OOOOOOOOPPPPSSSS((((UUUU1111))))             LLLLSSSS----DDDDOOOOSSSS 6666 ---- UUUUttttiiiilllliiiittttiiiieeeessss 1111              OOOOOOOOPPPPSSSS((((UUUU1111))))



     NNNNaaaammmmeeee
          OOPS - Allows a previously-typed DOS command to be edited.

     SSSSyyyynnnnttttaaaaxxxx
          ooooooooppppssss

     DDDDeeeessssccccrrrriiiippppttttiiiioooonnnn
          _O_o_p_s provides a convenient method of correcting a mistyped
          command without retyping the entire command.  This is also
          useful when performing repeated operations where only a
          small part of a command changes, such as a filename.  _O_o_p_s
          allows you to edit any line that is still on the screen.

          When _o_o_p_s is invoked, the <UP-ARROW> and <DOWN-ARROW> keys
          allow you to move the cursor to the line that is to be
          edited.  When the cursor is over the desired line, press
          <ENTER>, <F3> or <.>.  (<ENTER> clears the screen below the
          selected line while <F3> and <.> do not.)

          Once a line has been selected, it may be edited. _O_o_p_s uses
          the same editing commands that are available in the EDIT
          command in BASIC.

          Several of the commands accept an optional count.  By
          entering a one or two digit number prior to the command,
          that command will be performed the specified number of
          times.  As the number is entered, it is displayed at the
          bottom of the screen.  The commands that accept a count are
          noted by [_n].


          General commands:

          <<<<EEEENNNNTTTTEEEERRRR>>>>
               Signals that editing is complete and the command is
               passed to the operating system command interpreter.

          <<<<BBBBRRRREEEEAAAAKKKK>>>>
               Exits _o_o_p_s without performing any operation.  If _o_o_p_s
               is in a special mode, the first time the <BREAK> key is
               pressed exits the special mode and the second <BREAK>
               exits _o_o_p_s.  If _o_o_p_s is in a special mode, a message is
               displayed at the bottom of the screen.  For example, if
               the display shows the word "cccchhhhaaaannnnggggeeee", then _o_o_p_s is
               currently in the cccchhhhaaaannnnggggeeee mode.

          <<<<FFFF3333>>>> Exits any special mode _o_o_p_s may be in.  The current
               special mode (if any) is displayed in the lower-right
               cornet of the screen.  If _o_o_p_s is not in a special mode
               and <<<<FFFF3333>>>> is pressed, the <<<<FFFF3333>>>> is ignored.





