     OOOOOOOOPPPPSSSS((((UUUU1111))))             LLLLSSSS----DDDDOOOOSSSS 6666 ---- UUUUttttiiiilllliiiittttiiiieeeessss 1111              OOOOOOOOPPPPSSSS((((UUUU1111))))



          [_n]<<<<KKKK>>>>
               Searches for the next character that is typed and
               deletes the characters between the current position and
               the search-character.  If the character is not found,
               no characters are deleted.  If the character to search
               for is <<<<EEEENNNNTTTTEEEERRRR>>>>, all the characters to the right of the
               cursor are deleted.  Like the <<<<SSSS>>>> command, the search
               is case-sensitive.


          Movement commands:

          <<<<FFFF1111>>>> or <<<<LLLL>>>>
               Moves the cursor to the first column.

          <<<<FFFF2222>>>> Moves the cursor one column past the last character on
               the line.

          [_n]<<<<LLLLEEEEFFFFTTTT----AAAARRRRRRRROOOOWWWW>>>>
               Moves the cursor one position to the left.

          [_n]<<<<RRRRIIIIGGGGHHHHTTTT----AAAARRRRRRRROOOOWWWW>>>> or <<<<SSSSPPPPAAAACCCCEEEE>>>>
               Moves the cursor one position to the right.

     NNNNooootttteeeessss
          The Model 4 version of _o_o_p_s runs in the library overlay area
          and does not disturb memory below 0x2600 or above 0x2fff.
          The Model III version loads at 0x5800.

          Programs may invoke _o_o_p_s, but _o_o_p_s will not return control
          to them.  The status of the display is not altered by _o_o_p_s;
          therefore, if the cursor is off when _o_o_p_s is invoked, it
          will be difficult to use.  Reverse video text cannot be
          edited reliably, and may not be recognized by the operating
          system command interpreter.

          To install _o_o_p_s as the _I_m_m_e_d_i_a_t_e _E_x_e_c_u_t_i_o_n _P_r_o_g_r_a_m (IEP) in
          LS-DOS, use the command:
                COPY OOPS/CMD SYS13/SYS:0 (C=N)

          Once done, _o_o_p_s can be invoked by typing:       * <ENTER>

          _O_o_p_s uses the @VDCTL SVC in LS-DOS or a scan of video memory
          in Model III operating systems to read the contents of the
          screen, thus allowing it to edit commands other than the
          last command entered.  The edited command is supplied to the
          operating system via the @CMNDI call or SVC.


     FFFFiiiilllleeeessss
          No files are accessed by _o_o_p_s.




